TCS NQT PROGRAMMING & TECHNICAL CONCEPTS BLUEPRINT
Prepared by: TCS Senior Tester (10+ Years Experience)
Target Time-per-Question: 30 - 45 Seconds Benchmark (Pure Knowledge/Logic Marks)
================================================================================

TCS NQT includes an extensive set of questions checking core programming principles,
Data Structures, Algorithms, DBMS, Operating Systems, Networking, Software Engineering,
System Design, and emerging tech stacks. 

THE PRIMARY CHALLENGE: These questions test precise conceptual boundaries. You either 
know the mechanism or you do not. Because there are no lengthy calculations like 
Quantitative Aptitude, you must solve these in under 30-40 seconds to bank valuable 
time for the rest of your adaptive test framework.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🟥 TIER 1: CORE LANGUAGE MECHANICS & OBJECT-ORIENTED PROGRAMMING (OOP)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Guaranteed questions. Focuses on OOP pillars, language-specific executions (Java, 
Python, JavaScript), memory syntax, and evaluation conventions.

1. Pillars of OOP
   - Core Concepts: Encapsulation (hiding implementation details via data bundling),
     Abstraction (showing necessary features while hiding complexity), Inheritance 
     (acquiring parent properties), Polymorphism (entities taking multiple forms).
   - Java Specifics: Interfaces (completely abstract blueprints with abstract methods), 
     Abstract classes (can contain both abstract and concrete methods), Constructors 
     (object initialization), Method Overloading (same name, different parameters), 
     'final' keyword constraints, Static variables (shared across all instances), 
     Packages (namespaces organizing classes).
   - 60s Solvability: Extremely Easy (15 - 30 seconds).

2. Scripting & Language Dynamics (Python & JavaScript Foundations)
   - Core Concepts: Python operators (// for floor division dropping decimals), 
     List (mutable) vs Tuple (immutable) structures, Lambda (anonymous expressions). 
     JavaScript runtime mechanics (Hoisting, Closures giving access to outer scopes, 
     Promises representing async completion, Document Object Model / DOM tree interfaces), 
     String Immutability conventions, reference comparison (==) vs content evaluation (.equals()).
   - 60s Solvability: Easy (25 - 45 seconds).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🟨 TIER 2: DATA STRUCTURES & ALGORITHMIC PARADIGMS (The Advanced Screeners)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Directly influences your evaluation for Digital and Prime profiles. Tests your memory of 
complexities, traversal structures, and spatial memory trade-offs.

3. Data Structure Architectures
   - Linear Structures: Arrays (constant O(1) time indexing access), Stacks (LIFO principle), 
     Queues (FIFO principle used in BFS configurations), Linked Lists (constant O(1) time insertion 
     at the beginning, non-existence of a 'Binary Linked List'). Hash Tables (Hash collisions when 
     keys map to identical hashes, HashMap structural pairs).
   - Non-Linear Structures: Binary Trees (Preorder traversal: Root -> Left -> Right), Complete Binary 
     Trees (all levels filled left-to-right), skewed trees (worst-case height of n nodes).
   - 60s Solvability: Moderate (35 - 55 seconds).

4. Sorting, Searching & Algorithm Design
   - Search & Traversal: Linear Search (O(n) worst case), Binary Search (O(log n), strictly requires sorted data), 
     Breadth-First Search (uses Queues), Depth-First Search.
   - Sorting Complexities: Quick Sort (fastest on average O(n log n)), Merge Sort (stable sorting via divide-and-conquer). 
     Bubble, Selection, and Insertion sort mechanics.
   - Design Frameworks: Recursion (functions calling themselves, requiring a base case to prevent stack overflow), 
     Recursive Factorial space complexity (O(n) call stack), Dynamic Programming (solving overlapping subproblems), 
     Memoization (storing expensive call results), Greedy Approach (Dijkstra's shortest path, Kruskal's MST), 
     Backtracking (undoing choices when paths fail, Tower of Hanoi solutions).
   - 60s Solvability: Moderate to Hard (45 - 65 seconds).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🟦 TIER 3: RELATIONAL DATABASES (DBMS) & SYSTEM DESIGN FOUNDATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Highly structured questions checking data organization patterns and scalable corporate application layouts.

5. Database Management Systems (DBMS) & SQL
   - Syntax & Rules: SQL (Structured Query Language), DDL (CREATE, ALTER, DROP) vs DML (INSERT), 
     SELECT for retrieval, WHERE vs HAVING clause filtering.
   - Architecture: RDBMS systems, Primary Keys (unique identification), UNIQUE constraints, 
     FULL OUTER JOIN (matching records across either table), Normalization (reducing redundancy), 
     INDEX utilization (speeding up queries), Transactions (sequences executed as a single logical unit).
   - 60s Solvability: Easy (30 - 45 seconds).

6. System Design Architecture Basics
   - Routing & Distribution: Load balancing (workload distribution across systems), CDN (geographically 
     distributed content delivery networks), Message Queues (asynchronous communication between separate microservices).
   - Scalability Metrics: Horizontal scaling (adding more machines/scaling out), Vertical scaling (adding power 
     to an existing machine/scaling up), Database Sharding (partitioning data tables across distinct servers), 
     Eventual Consistency, Stateless Architecture layout (servers retaining zero client state between requests).
   - 60s Solvability: Moderate (40 - 60 seconds).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
⬛ TIER 4: SOFTWARE ENGINEERING, NETWORKING, CYBERSECURITY & CORE DOMAINS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Tests execution pipelines, deployment architectures, protocol handshakes, and baseline terminology.

7. Software Engineering & Agile Methodology
   - Frameworks: SDLC (Waterfall sequential model vs Agile/Scrum flexible sprint iterations). 
     Project metrics (User stories, acceptance criteria conditions, sprint retrospectives, burndown charts tracking work).
   - Git Workflows: Version control tracking (Git distributed engine, GitHub hosting platform).
   - Testing Disciplines: Unit testing (individual component validation), Integration testing (combined module checks), 
     Regression testing (re-testing to ensure existing code didn't break), Black Box testing (functional assessment 
     without inside structural access), TDD (Test-Driven Development), Code Coverage metrics, Refactoring (restructuring 
     code without modifying external runtime outcomes), Technical Debt (future rework cost from quick hacks), Pair Programming.
   - 60s Solvability: Easy (30 - 50 seconds).

8. Computer Networks & Core Infrastructure
   - Protocols & Systems: IP (Internet Protocol), DNS (Domain Name System), LAN (Local Area Network), FTP, HTTP (port 80), 
     HTTPS (secure port 443 via SSL/TLS), SMTP (sending emails), bandwidth capabilities (data volume transfer speed).
   - OSI Layers & Hardware: OSI Layer 2 (Data Link - Switches operate here, unique physical MAC addressing), 
     OSI Layer 3 (Network - Routers operate here, handles IP routing paths), Subnet masks (separating network/host parts), 
     Class A private ranges (10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255).
   - 60s Solvability: Easy to Moderate (35 - 55 seconds).

9. Operating Systems (OS) & Logic Fundamentals
   - Core Mechanics: OS operations (Memory, Process, File management), Deadlocks (infinite waiting loops for mutual resources), 
     FCFS (non-preemptive scheduling), Virtual Memory (extending RAM via disk allocation), Thrashing (excessive page faulting loops), 
     Linux commands (`ps` for process tracking), Semaphores (synchronization blocks), Cache Memory (fastest local hierarchy access), 
     Multi-user OS environments (Linux), Context Switching (saving and restoring state vectors).
   - Hardware Fundamentals: CPU structures, volatile vs non-volatile storage (RAM vs ROM/Hard Disks), 
     Bit systems (8 bits = 1 byte), base systems (Hexadecimal base-16), firmware ROM chips, 
     logic gates (AND gate tracking), clock speed evaluations (Hertz), compilation vs interpretation pipelines, 
     error states (Syntax structure errors, Runtime execution exceptions, Logical incorrect calculation outcomes), 
     Pseudocode descriptions, Flowcharts (Ovals for terminal boundaries, Diamonds for conditional logic blocks), Debugging setups.
   - Modern Tech Stacks: Big data ecosystems, Blockchain ledgers, IoT devices, DevOps cultures, Docker containers, Microservices.
   - Cybersecurity: Encryption ciphers, Firewalls, Phishing hooks, Malware & Ransomware payloads, Two-Factor Authentication (2FA), 
     DDoS service floods, injection vulnerabilities (SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting / XSS, Cross-Site Request Forgery / CSRF), OAuth tokens, JWT.
   - AI & Machine Learning: Supervised learning (Linear Regression), Unsupervised tools (Clustering/K-Means), Overfitting pitfalls 
     (high training data score, poor generalization), Neural networks (modeled on human brain), Deep Learning, NLP, Computer Vision.
   - 60s Solvability: Moderate (40 - 60 seconds).

